## Post anatomy and YAML front matter

Every post is an `index.qmd` file inside a dated directory under `posts/`. The canonical front matter skeleton:

```yaml
---
title: "Post Title"
date: 2026-06-05
description: "One or two sentences."
categories:
  - data-science
  - r
status: draft
publish_to:
  - erwinlares
  - brug
---
```

**`status`** is the safety gate. The dispatch layer ignores any post where `status` is not `published`. Always start with `draft`; change to `published` only when the post is ready to go.

**`publish_to`** controls routing. List only the platforms this particular post should reach. Valid values are `erwinlares`, `brug`, `lasrubieraspottery`, and `researchci`. Adding a new platform to an existing post and re-running `publish()` will dispatch only to the new platform — `dispatch_log.csv` prevents re-sending to platforms that have already received the post.

**`categories`** drives taxonomy and tag filtering on the site. The canonical tag set is:

`personal`, `data-science`, `linguistics`, `pottery`, `aikido`, `r`, `brug`, `reproducibility`, `productivity`, `coding`, `journal`

The `journal` tag carries special behavior: it populates the dynamic "From the Journal" section on the About page via a Quarto listing filter. Any post tagged `journal` will appear there automatically.

